{"title_page": "Davis Entertainment", "text_new": "{{short description|American film production company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Davis Entertainment\n| logo = \n| type = \n| industry = Film production, television production\n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = 1984\n| founder = [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]]\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Davis Entertainment''' is an American [[film]] and [[television series|television]] [[production company]], founded by [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]] in 1984.\n\nDavis's three divisions\u2013feature film, independent film, and television\u2013develop and produce film and television projects for the major studios, independent distributors, networks and cable broadcasters. The company itself has enjoyed a long-standing first-look production deal at [[20th Century Fox]], although it also produces projects for all studios and mini-majors.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Predator (film)|Predator]]'' (1987)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Kinsey|first=Michelle|url=https://newspapers.com/clip/44013830/the_star_press/|title=Hometown cat Garfield's movie opens next week|date=June 5, 2004|work=The Star Press|access-date=|url-status=live|publisher=Gannett|issue=362|location=Muncie, Indiana|volume=105|pages=1, 6|via=Newspapers.com}}  Note - the link provided is to part two of the article; [https://newspapers.com/clip/44013890/the_star_press/ part one is located here].</ref>\n* ''[[Three O'Clock High]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[License to Drive]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Little Monsters]]'' (1989)\n* ''Curiosity Kills'' (1990) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Dangerous Passion]]'' (1990) (TV movie) \n* ''[[Silhouette]]'' (1990) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Enid Is Sleeping]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[The Last of the Finest]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Predator 2]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Shattered (1991 film)|Shattered]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Fortress (1992 film)|Fortress]]'' (1992)\n* ''Wild Card'' (1992) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Storyville (film)|Storyville]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[The Firm (1993 film)|The Firm]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Thing Called Love]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Last Outlaw (1993 film)|The Last Outlaw]]'' (1993) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Grumpy Old Men (film)|Grumpy Old Men]]'' (1993)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* ''[[Voyage (1993 film)|Voyage]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[This Can't Be Love (film)|This Can't Be Love]]'' (1994) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Gunmen (1994 film)|Gunmen]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[One Christmas]]'' (1994) (TV movie)\n* ''Tears and Laughter: The Joan and Melissa Rivers Story'' (1994) (TV movie)\n* ''New Eden'' (1994) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Richie Rich (film)|Richie Rich]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Hunted (1995 film)|The Hunted]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Waterworld]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Grumpier Old Men]]'' (1995)\n*''[[The Grass Harp (film)|The Grass Harp]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Denise Calls Up]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Chamber (1996 film)|The Chamber]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Daylight (1996 film)|Daylight]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Courage Under Fire]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Out to Sea]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Digging to China]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Lewis and Clark and George]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Asteroid (film)|Asteroid]]'' (1997) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Volcano: Fire on the Mountain]]'' (1997) (TV movie)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reich|first=Kenneth|url=https://newspapers.com/clip/44017677/the_los_angeles_times/|title=Mammoth Area Avoids Fallout From 'Volcano'|date=March 3, 1997|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=|url-status=live|publisher=Times Mirror Company|issue=90|edition=Valley|volume=CXVI|pages=F9, F15|via=Newspapers.com}}  Note - [https://newspapers.com/clip/44017720/the_los_angeles_times/ Link to second part of the article].</ref>\n* ''[[Ba